\subsection{Proof of Theorem \ref{main}}\noindent  Now by Theorem \ref{dim} and  Lemma \ref{filk} and Remark \ref{global} we have that  $K_0({\textnormal{Fil}^0(D_r(G,K))}) \simeq G_0({\textnormal{Fil}^0(D_r(G,K))})=\mathbb{Z}^c$. Hence by the Localization sequence that we used may times we have a surjective map $\xi: \mathbb{Z}^c \to G_0({D_{r}(G,K)})$. By Remark \ref{global} and Theorem \ref{dglob} we have that $K_0({D_{r}(G,K)}) \simeq G_0({D_{r}(G,K)})$. Unfortunately we cannot use the proof we have in the continuous case since the quotient ring ${\textnormal{Fil}^0(D_r(G,K))}/{\textnormal{Fil}^0(D_r(G,K))}\cdot p$ has infinite global dimension. But we have Theorem $5.2.$ in \cite{S1} so by the faithfully flatness property we have a map  $K_0(K[[G]]) \hookrightarrow K_0({D_{r}(G,K)})$ and it is injective. By Proposition \ref{kcomp} we have both an injective and a surjective map between $\mathbb{Z}^c$ and $K_0({D_{r}(G,K)})$. These are all abelian groups hence $\mathbb{Z}$-modules. Using the structure theorem of finitely generated module over a PID we get an isomorphism $\mathbb{Z}^c \simeq K_0({D_{r}(G,K)})$. 
